@Node "XarsArchiverInfo()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsArchiverInfo"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsArchiverInfo()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        info = XarsArchiverInfo()
         D0

        struct XarSubInfo *XarsArchiverInfo(void)

@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Returns information about the archiver.

        You must fill out the following fields:


        struct XarSubInfo {

           USHORT Sizeof;           /* sizeof(XarArchiverInfo)            */

           USHORT SubVersion;       /* Version of the sublib              */
           USHORT SubRevision;      /* Revision of the sublib             */
           USHORT MasterVersion;    /* Required xpkarchive.library version*/

           struct XarArchiverInfo XarInfo;

           struct XpkMode *ModeDesc;/* @{"List" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:exec/lists.h/Main" 21} of individual mode descriptors*/

           UBYTE *Identify[8];      /* Indentify-patterns                 */

        };


        Where XarInfo is:

        struct XarArchiverInfo {

           UBYTE  Name[24];        /* Brief name of the packer, 20 char max*/
           UBYTE  LongName[32];    /* Full name of the packer   30 char max*/
           UBYTE  Description[80]; /* Short packer desc., 70 char max      */

           UBYTE  ArchiveType[24]; /* Archive-type e.g.: lha, zoo, ...     */
           UBYTE  ID[9];           /* ID the packer goes by (XAR format)   */
           UWORD  DefaultMode;     /* default packmode                     */

           LONG   Flags;           /* flags for supported input/output     */
                                   /* capabilities  (XARIF_...)            */
        };

@{b}    NOTES@{ub}

      - You must supply at least one identify-pattern and up to eight
        identify patterns. They are used to find out the type of a file
        after it has been opened and before any sublib is loaded.

        This pattern is just a string. Every character in the string must
        exactly match a byte in the file with the following excepions:

            '?' matches any character
            '*' is an escape character and together with the following
                byte it is used to match groups of characters:

              sequence   matches               c-equivalent

               '*d'    : digit                 isdigit
               '*x'    : xdigit                isxdigit
               '*a'    : alpha                 isalpha
               '*n'    : alphanumeric          isalnum
               '*l'    : lower                 islower
               '*u'    : upper                 isupper
               '*c'    : cntrl                 iscntrl
               '*g'    : graphic character     isgraph
               '*p'    : printable             isprint
               '*.'    : punctuation           ispunct
               '*s'    : space                 isspace
               '*?'    : ?
               '**'    : *
               '*0'    : zero

          e.g.  "T?ST*d**" will match "TEST0*","ToST2*","T_ST4*"
                           but not "TESTx*" or "lkajhsfd"


        Your sublib will be loaded, if one of the 8 patterns matches the
        contents of the file. Then XarsOpenArchive of your sublib will be
        called and you can do further checking to test, if this file can
        be handled by your sublib.

        It is very important, that your patterns match the file as good
        as possible. The reason for this is, that all sublibs, whose
        patterns match the file, will get loaded into memory, till the
        first one successfully opens the archive. Although, they are
        removed by ramlib, when you run out of memory, it has some
        negative effects: The system will use slow CHIP-memory before
        it removes your unused library and the largest block of memory
        may become smaller as your library gets loaded. Now think of
        10 sublibs having "" as a pattern. Now every XarOpenArchive will
        load all these 10 libraries into memory. If these sublibs require
        20kBytes each, you have just wasted 200kBytes of memory, you see
        what I mean ?


      - ModeDesc must contain a pointer to a list of struct XpkMode. The
        last element of this list must have the "Upto"-field set to 100.
        Some fields are only relevant for XPK-packers like e.g. ChunkSize
        and should be set to 0. (see also libraries/xpk.h)

      - Flags must contain the supported input/output types. You must at
        least support compression from memory to the archive (XARIF_PK_MEM)
        and decompression from the archive to memory (XARIF_UP_MEM).

        You may support compression from a filehandle to the archive via
        XARIF_PK_STREAM, and decompression with XARIF_UP_STREAM. The same
        applies to XARIF_PK_HOOK.

        Input/Output types that are not supported by your lib will be
        transformed to (de)compression (to)from memory by the
        xpkarchive.library.


@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

       info - a pointer to the initialized structure


@{b}    SEE ALSO@{ub}

       libraries/xpk.h, libraries/xpkarchive.h, libraries/xpkarchivesub.h


@EndNode

@Node "XarsCreateArchive()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsCreateArchive"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsCreateArchive()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsCreateArchive(arc)
         D0                   A0

        LONG XarsCreateArchive(struct XarSubHandle *)


@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

         Create an empty archive and initialize the XarSubHandle.
         You may use the "Sub"-fields to store information needed by
         your library.

         arc->ArcFile contains the file-handle of the archive.
         arc->SubLibs contains a pointer to your sublib.

         your sublib will be opened once per archive !


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

         arc - partly initialized XarSubHandle


@{b}    NOTE@{ub}

         You may replace arc->ArcFile with a new filehandle or NULL, as
         long as you follow some rules:

         - You must not return an error-code >=XARERROR_LEVEL, if you have
           modified arc->Arcfile.

         - The xpkarchive.library will call Close for the filehandle in
           arc->ArcFile, if it is not NULL. Therefore if you close the
           File yourself, then you must set this entry to NULL.



@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

         error-code

@EndNode

@Node "XarsOpenArchive()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsOpenArchive"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsOpenArchive()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsOpenArchive(arc)
         D0                   A0

        LONG XarsOpenArchive(struct XarSubHandle *)


@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

         Open the archive and initialize the XarSubHandle.
         You may use the "Sub"-fields to store information needed by
         your library.

         If the archive is not known by your lib, you must return
         XARERR_UNKNOWN_TYPE. You need not restore the file-position.


         The XarSubHandle structure has the following fields:

         struct XarSubHandle { /* Archive-handle */

         /* public */

            BPTR  ArcFile;
            UBYTE *ArchiveName;       /* Read only ! */
            ULONG OpenMode;           /* Read only ! */
            ULONG Flags;              /* XARAF_...   */

            struct @{"Library" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:exec/libraries.h/Main" 34} *MasterLib; /* Read only ! */
            struct @{"Library" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:exec/libraries.h/Main" 34} *SubLib;    /* Read only ! */

            struct @{"MinList" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:exec/lists.h/Main" 32} ArcLocks;

            ULONG Reserved[8];

            ULONG Sub[4];              /* For private use of sublibs */

         };


         The fields have the following values:

         ArcFile:     file-handle of the archive
         ArchiveName: filename of the archive
         OpenMode:    open-mode given by the user
         Flags:       flags supported by now:
                      XARAF_Corrupt, XARAF_ShowDirs
                      If you detect some errors in the archive, you should
                      set XARAF_Corrupt. This inhibits the adding of new
                      files to a corrupt archive.
         MasterLib:   library-base of the xpkarchive.library
         SubLib:      library-base of your sub-library
         Arclocks:    empty list
         Reserved[8]: reserved for future use, do not use !!!
         Sub[4]:      for use of your sublibrary, initialized to 0

         your sublib will be opened once per archive !

         This function must also build the list of files in the archive.
         Therefore it must add initialized XarSubLock sructures to
         arc->ArcLocks, e.g. with:

         AddTail((struct @{"List" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:exec/lists.h/Main" 21} *)&arc->ArcLocks,(struct @{"Node" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:exec/nodes.h/Main" 23} *)lock);


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

         arc - partly initialized XarSubHandle


@{b}    NOTE@{ub}

         You may replace arc->ArcFile with a new filehandle or NULL, as
         long as you follow some rules:

         - You must not return an error-code >=XARERROR_LEVEL, if you have
           modified arc->Arcfile.

         - The xpkarchive.library will call Close for the filehandle in
           arc->ArcFile, if it is not NULL. Therefore if you close the
           File yourself, then you must set this entry to NULL.


@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

         error-code

@EndNode

@Node "XarsCloseArchive()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsCloseArchive"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsCloseArchive()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsCloseArchive(arc)
         D0                   A0

        LONG XarsCloseArchive(struct XarSubHandle *)


@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Close the archive and free all allocated resources i.e. the list
        of files in arc->ArcLocks.


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        arc - initialized XarSubHandle

@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        error-code

@EndNode

@Node "XarsAddDir()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsAddDir"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsAddDir()


@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsAddDir(arc, xio, lock)
         D0             A0  A1    A2

        LONG XarsAddDir(struct XarSubHandle *,struct XarSubIO *,struct XarSubLock **)


@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Add a directory to the archive.
        Allocate a XarSubLockStructure and return this via *lock.

        If you need some additional fields in the lock, just add them after
        the XarSubLock and allocate enough memory to hold them.

        You would do something like:

        newlock=AllocMem(...)
        *newlock=**lock; /* pre initialize your lock */

        /* initialize newlock according to your needs */

        *lock=newlock; /* return lock */

        You should call the progress report-function XarProgress()
        (see also the xardummy.library)


        Furthermore it must add this entry to the list of files in
        the archive (arc->Arclocks) e.g. with:

        AddTail((struct @{"List" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:exec/lists.h/Main" 21} *)&arc->ArcLocks,(struct @{"Node" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:exec/nodes.h/Main" 23} *)lock);


@{b}    IMPORTANT@{ub}

        You must not leave *lock unchanged, since it is only
        temporay and it is freed after the call to your
        function, unless you return an error-code.


@{b}    NOTE@{ub}

        The directoryname, that is passed to this function will always
        end in '/'.


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        arc  - pointer to XarSubHandle of the archive
        xio  - pointer to XarSubIO needed to call XarProgress.
        lock - pointer to a pointer to an initialized XarSubLock structure.

@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        XarSubLock via *lock.

        error-code or XARERROR_FUNCTION_NOT_SUPPORTED

@EndNode

@Node "XarsAddFile()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsAddFile"


@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsAddFile()


@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsAddFile(arc,xio,lock)
         D0             A0  A1   A2

        LONG XarsAddFile(struct XarSubHandle *,struct XarSubIO *,
                         struct XarSubLock **)


@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Add a file to the archive.
        Allocate a XarSubLockStructure and return this via *lock.

        If you need some additional fields in the lock, just add them after
        XarSubLock and allocate enough memory to hold them.

        You would do something like:

        newlock=AllocMem(...)
        *newlock=**lock; /* pre initialize your lock */

        /* initialize newlock according to your needs */

        *lock=newlock; /* return lock */


        xio contains the missing informations needed to add the file to
        the archive.

        One of IOMem, IOStream of IOHook is !=0. This one specifies the
        kind of input/output. If you do not find a supported input/output
        type, then you must return XARERR_INPUT_NOT_SUPPORTED;

        You should call the progress report-function XarProgress().


        Furthermore it must add this entry to the list of files in
        the archive (arc->Arclocks) e.g. with:

        AddTail((struct @{"List" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:exec/lists.h/Main" 21} *)&arc->ArcLocks,(struct @{"Node" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:exec/nodes.h/Main" 23} *)lock);


@{b}    IMPORTANT@{ub}

        You must not leave *lock unchanged, since it is only
        temporarly and it is freed after the call to your
        function, unless you return an error-code.


@{b}    NOTE@{ub}

        The filename passed to this function will not end in '/'.



@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        arc  - pointer to XarSubHandle of the archive
        xio  - pointer to XarSubIO
        lock - pointer to a pointer to an initialized XarSubLock structure.

@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        XarSubLock via *lock.

        error-code

@EndNode

@Node "XarsCmpFilename()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsCmpFilename"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsCmpFilename()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        cmp = XarsCmpFilename(name1,name2)
         D0                    A0    A1

        LONG XarsCmpFilename(UBYTE *,UBYTE *)

@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Compare two filenames. This function is required to support
        the different handling of filenames on different architectures.
        E.g. unix has case-sensitive filenames.

@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        name1, name2 - pointers to two filenames


@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        <0  if name1<name2
        ==0 if name1==name2
        >0  if name1>name2

@EndNode

@Node "XarsCopyFile()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsCopyFile"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsCopyFile(lock,arc) (a0,a1)


@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsCopyFile(lock,arc)
        D0                A0   A1

        LONG XarsCopyFile(struct XarSubLock **,struct XarSubHandle *)


@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Copy a file from one archive to another. You must allocate a
        new lock for the second archive and return it via *lock, unless
        you return an error-code.

@{b}    IMPORTANT !!@{ub}

        The xpkarchive.library may temporarly set a new filename,
        a new filenote and a new generation in **lock. This is used to
        set a new filename or filenote when copying files using this funtion.


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        lock - pointer to a pointer to a XarSubLock. (*lock)->Arc contains
               a pointer to the source-archive.

        dstarc - pointer to the destination-archive


@{b}    NOTE@{ub}

        This function is called with dstarc->SubLib in a6 rather than
        srcarc->SubLib !



@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        error-code

@EndNode

@Node "XarsDeleteFile()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsDeleteFile"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsDeleteFile()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsDeleteFile(lock)
         D0                 A0

        LONG XarsDeleteFile(struct XarSubLock *)

@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Delete a file or mark a file as deleted in the archive.


@{b}    NOTE@{ub}

        This function will never be called for already deleted files.


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        lock - XarSubLock to the file to be deleted


@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        error-code, XARERR_FUNCTION_NOT_SUPPORTED, if your archive does
        not support the deletion of files


@EndNode

@Node "XarsDirect()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsDirect"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsDirect()


@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        err = XarsDirect(handle,command)
        D0                A0      A1

        LONG XarsDirect(XarHandle *,UBYTE *)


@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        This function is used access special functions in your sublibrary.
        You get a commandline in 'command'.


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}
        handle  - Handle of the archive
        command - Commandstring


@{b}    RESULT@{ub}
        err - Error code


@{b}    NOTE@{ub}
        The error code needs not really indicate an error, but for this
        function it is also used to indicate, that there is a result-text
        from the function. Errorcodes>=XARERR_CUSTOM_LEVEL are custom error
        codes of the sublibraries and the same error-code may result in
        a different result-message every time.


@{b}    SEE ALSO@{ub}

        The sourcecode for the xarZOO.library uses this function to implement
        the generation-handling functions.


@EndNode

@Node "XarsExamine()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsExamine"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsExamine()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsExamine(lock,xfib)
         D0              A0   A1

        LONG XarsExamine(struct XarSubLock *, struct XpkFib *)


@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Emulate XpkExamine for your archive. You should fill xfib with
        some sensible values or return XARERR_FUNCTION_NOT_SUPPORTED.


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        lock - XarSubLock of the file
        xfib - XpkFibStructure, that you should write your values to

@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        error-code, XARERR_FUNCTION_NOT_SUPPORTED, if your archive does
        not support this function

@EndNode

@Node "XarsExtractFile()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsExtractFile"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}

        XarsExtractFile()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsExtractFile(lock,xio)
        D0                   A0   A1


        LONG XarsExtractFile(struct XarSubLock *, struct XarSubIO *)

@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Extract a file from an archive to memory, a file or using
        a hook-function.

        xio contains the missing informations needed to extract the file
        from the archive.

        One of IOMem, IOStream of IOHook is !=0. This one specifies the
        kind of input/output. If you do not find a supported input/output
        type, then you must return XARERR_OUTPUT_NOT_SUPPORTED;

        You should call the progress report-function XarProgress().


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        xio  - pointer to XarSubIO
        lock - pointer to a pointer to an initialized XarSubLock structure.


@{b}    NOTE@{ub}

        The xpkarchive.library will extract the date and comment if
        decompressed to a file.


@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        error-code

@EndNode

@Node "XarsModifyFileData()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsModifyFileData"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsModifyFileData(lock,fdata)(a0,a1)

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsModifyFileData(lock,fdata)
        D0                      A0   A1

        LONG XarsModifyFileData(struct XarSubLock *,struct XarExtFileData *)

@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Modify values in lock according to fdata, which holds the modified
        values.


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        lock  - pointer to XarSubLock structure of the file
        fdata - holds the new values


@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        error-code, XARERR_FUNCTION_NOT_SUPPORTED, if your archive does
        not support this kind of function.


@{b}    SEE ALSO@{ub}

         XarsDeleteFile XarsUndeleteFile
@EndNode

@Node "XarsPackArchive()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsPackArchive"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}

        XarsPackArchive()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsPackArchive(from,to)
         D0                  A0  A1

        LONG XarsPackArchive(struct XarSubHandle *, struct XarSubHandle *)


@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Copy all information, but deleted files and other unused information,
        from the archive 'from' to the archive 'to'. Note that the archive
        'to' need not be empty !

@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        from, to -  XarSubHandles of the archives.


@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        error-code

@EndNode

@Node "XarsRenameFile()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsRenameFile"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsRenameFile()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsRenameFile(lock,newname,newgen)
         D0                 A0    A1     D0

        LONG XarsRenameFile(struct XarSubLock *, UBYTE *, LONG)


@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Rename the file in the archive and set a new generationnumber.


@{b}    NOTE@{ub}

        - The generationnumber need not be different from the old one.


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        lock - XarSubLock of the file in the archive
        newname - new filename
        newgen  - new generationnumber


@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        error-code

@EndNode

@Node "XarsSetFilenote()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsSetFilenote"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}

        XarsSetFilenote()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsSetFilenote(lock,note)
        D0                   A0   A1

        LONG XarsSetFilenote(struct XarSubLock *, UBYTE *note)


@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Set a new filenote for the file


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        lock - XarSubLock of the file
        note - new filenote


@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        error-code, XARERR_FUNCTION_NOT_SUPPORTED
@EndNode

@Node "XarsUndeleteFile()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsUndeleteFile"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarsUndeleteFile()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        err=XarsUndeleteFile(lock)
         D0                 A0

        LONG XarsUndeleteFile(struct XarSubLock *)

@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Undelete a file or mark a file as undeleted in the archive.


@{b}    NOTE@{ub}

        This function will only be called for deleted files.


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        lock - XarSubLock to the file to be undeleted


@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        error-code, XARERR_FUNCTION_NOT_SUPPORTED, if your archive does
        not support the undeletion of files

@EndNode

@Node "XarsWhy()" "xpkarcsub.library/XarsWhy"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}

        XarsWhy()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        errorstring = XarsWhy(arc,error)
            D0                 A0   D0

        UBYTE * XarsWhy(struct XarSubHandle *, LONG )


@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Return a description for a custom error-code of your sublibrary.


@{b}    NOTE@{ub}

        The error-code refers to the last error, that occured.

        If you don't generate custom error-codes, then you should return
        NULL.

        You may return different error-messages for the same error-code,
        everytime this function gets called.


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        arc   - XarSubHandle of the archive
        error - custom error-code


@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        Pointer to description or NULL

@EndNode

@Node "--general--()" "xpkarcsub.library/--general--"


@{b}   What's got to be supported by a sublibrary@{ub}


      The interface to XAR-sublibs was designed to support different types
      of archives. Therefore not all functions are useful for all types of
      archives. E.g. not all archives support generations. If your archive
      does not support a specific function, then your function should return
      XARERR_FUNCTION_NOT_SUPPORTED to indicate that this function is not
      supported by this kind of archive (except for XarsWhy, which should
      return NULL in this case). However there are some functions,
      that must be present and functional for the proper handling of
      archives. These are:


         XarsArchiverInfo, XarsCreateArchive, XarsOpenArchive,
         XarsCloseArchive, XarsAddFile, XarsCmpFilename, XarsExtractFile

         (These functions must not return XARERR_FUNCTION_NOT_SUPPORTED)



      Functions, that are not 'a must', but that are really useful:

         XarsCopyFile, XarsDeleteFile, XarsUndeleteFile, XarsPackArchive

         NOTE: If you do not support XarsPack archive, the default-behaviour
               is to copy all files using XarsCopyFile.



      Functions that depend on what your archive-type supports:

         XarsAddDir, XarsModifyFileData, XarsExamine, XarsModifyFileData,
         XarsNextGeneration, XarsRenameFile, XarsSetFilenote




@{b}    Some general notes@{ub}

        Some notes about the file-list

        -  The order of the files in the archive must not change, except
           that an 'arclock' may be removed from the list when a file gets
           deleted.

        -  New files are added to the end of the file-list.



@{b}   Progress-report:@{ub}

      You should call XarProgress when packing or unpacking files or when
      you add directories, since this calls the progress-hook, that was
      set by the programmer and that gives the user some feedback of
      what's going on. See the docs of XarProgress in the xpkarchive.library
      for more inforemation.




@{b}   Error-Codes@{ub}

      The xpkarchive.library offers quite a long list of error-codes. If you
      do not find a suitable error-code you may return your own custom
      error-code. These error-codes have a value above XARERR_CUSTOM_LEVEL.
      But since the xpkarchive.library has no chance to know, what this
      error-code means, but has to return an error-string when the user
      calls XarWhy, it needs to get a description of the error. Therefore
      it calls XarsWhy of the sublibrary. Therefore if you do not use
      custom error-codes, XarsWhy will not be called (however you should
      return NULL, if this should really happen). In the other case you
      must return a descriptive text of the error.


@EndNode

